data.title: Chinese food on the cheap
data.text: Good food, very reasonable prices, hot and sour soup is a must. Great little bakery with Asian goodies.

data.title: Really good place
data.text: We have been eating at Toy's Cafe for many years.  We have seen three location changes since the 60's  and the food has always been great!  Prices remain low and staff friendly.

data.title: Convenient locate, good food
data.text: This Chinese restaurant is right behind Bellevue Way/ Main Street. Their food is quite basic Chinese food. The flavor is good as well as the price. It is very convenient as they open late in the evening and they sell bakery too. When I live in downtown Bellevue, I always grab food from Toy's café on my way back home so I don't have to cook.

data.title: Chinese food at its best
data.text: I have eaten here and taken out many times. Extremely good food and a friendly atmosphere. There is also a bakery on site that has wonderful sweet baked items. A definite go to for Chinese.

data.title: Short delivered, short changed, bad services.
data.text:
Their lunch special is 1/3 cheaper than LaBuLa. It's fine if I get what I pay for. Turns out it was less than what I pay for.
The lunch special includes the soup, fried wonton, 1 entree, and rice. But they never brought the fried wonton. They don't check back with you either; not even an eye contact. Until they brought the bill, I asked if they forgot the fried wonton. The waitress said "Oh!" and turned away. Never said "sorry". About 5 minutes later she brought a small dish with a couple triangle pieces of fried wonton wrap (NOT fried wonton!). I have never seen such "fried wonton" at any Chinese restaurant!
When paying my bill, I should've getting $5.50 change. The old owner woman gave me back 50 cents only. When I questioned her math, she insisted she was right until i confronted her 3 times.
After all, from entering to leaving, there was no proper greetings, no smiles, not even a straight eye contact.
The food was typical American Chines with lots of MSG added. The portion was not big. I'd much rather spend a few more $ for a better lunch.

data.title: Prototype American Chinese restaurant.
data.text: I been going to this restaurant long before they moved from main street.  Remember? Most of the Chinese restaurant prior to 1999 were Cantonese since many of them came from Hong Kong. At the time, many of Chinese cooking were modified to accommodate American palate. Outcome of their efforts were Egg Foo Young, Chap Suey, Pepper Steak, Shrimp with Lobster sauce etc.  When I had enough of authentic Chinese food, I call for a takeout at this place.  Pork Egg Foo Young , Shrimp with Lobster sauce and Hot and Sour soup.  Almost identical stuff I had 40 years ago back in East Coast.  One less star is for their inconsistent service.

data.title: Wonderful restaurant
data.text: The food and service is great. A small spot so sometimes slow but great  great food and the staff really want to do the best they can.

data.title: Good for the price and quality of food
data.text: Very are regulars with the restaurant.  The food are consistent and pretty good for the price.  Don't expect 5-star service but good enough. I go back again for sure

data.title: Good cheap eats in Downtown Bellevue
data.text: I love the Sichuanese Beef Noodle and Tendon soup here.  Toy's Café has been in downtown Bellevue for many years.  Their food is consistently good and they offer a large variety.  They also have an excellent bakery.

data.title: A small, clean, good, modest Chinese restaurant in Bellevue
data.text: I have gone to Toys Cafe for more than 30 years.  It has an encyclopedic menu, and the quality is consistently well above average.  The prices are reasonable and the portions are big.  The  addition of an Asian bakery in their newest location on 106th is very nice and allows me to take home specialties for later in the week.  This place is our favorite Chinese place.  It is a true neighborhood restaurant owned by the same people for ever, and meeting all of our expectations for a pleasant, tasty economical dinner out.

data.title: One of the long time restuarants in Bellevue
data.text: 1st time I can recall eating at Toy's is late 1950's. With all the development in this city, they have moved a few times, but they are going to stay! I'm very glad for that. This is Chinese food you will remember, and it won't break the bank. Can't pass up the BBQ Pork.

data.title: OMG Good
data.text: Didn't realize how good the food would be. It was highly recommended, but not highly enough. Went with a large group of work friends for lunch. Good walking distance to and fro offices in downtown. Ate so much that the walk was really welcome. Again, very busy, so should reach before 12. Loved all the food we ordered. Beef soup was just amazing.

data.title: Finally found a great Chinese food place on the eastside
data.text: Tired of treading into Seattle's international district to get Mandarin style Chinese food, I tried Toy's Cafe in Bellevue. It's in a strip mall, so my expectations were low. The food was so amazing, I've been back twice! My favorites are crispy almond-fried chicken drizzled with light sauce,  hot and sour soup, and fried rice. Next time I will get more adventurous and try Egg Foo Young or the Hot Pot choices. I've tried Chinese food all over Redmond, K-land, and Bellevue, and this is my favorite by far! (And the prices were more than reasonable.)

data.title: New Location
data.text:
This was our first trip to Toy's .... but we couldnt find it at the Main Street location (that is now a hole in the ground pending construction of an apartment building). Luckily we found their new location at 131 106th Ave NE.

The food was very good especially the Moo Shoo (we had pork) but the General Tsu was "mama who who". The combo prices were most reasonable. The food is far better than the atmosphere and the atmosphere is better than the service. If you select a restaurant for the food Toys will not disappoint. There business is very good a lot of regular customers including celebrities. We will return.

data.title: solid authentic food
data.text: Toy's has been around forever, I remember going to their old town, main street location over fifty years ago. That longevity speaks well for it. In a new square location it has changed with the city but still retains it's good authentic food at a good price. The menu covers Cantonese, Mandarin and Szechuan cuisine either in family style or combination plates. Prices are very reasonable. This is a café meaning that the interior is not huge nor the atmosphere opulent, but it is all in good clean taste and it's all about the food - right?

data.title: best chineese for the price in bellevue
data.text: toys has been in bellevue since i've been in high school, excellent sweet and sour soup and the other food is very good as well, best chineese in town

data.title: Happy accident
data.text: We drove around looking for Joy and we came to this place not knowing we were at the wrong place, but as soon as we walked in we saw a full house with only Asian diners we knew we were at the right place. Not a fancy setting but food is above average, free hot tea like in any HK style yamcha place. Bakery is a plus if you need something easy to eat at the airport like we did.

data.title: Great Family Style Chinese Restaurant
data.text: Located near Bellevue's downtown, Toy's Cafe is one if my favorite Local restaurant to visit.  The space is light and open with plenty of free parking which is a big plus.  The menu is extensive but with many familiar Chinese dishes.  I enjoy mostly its family style dishes which include noodle soup, fried rice and stir fried Singapore rice noodle.  The appetizers are great.  I like the green onion pancake, pan fried dumplings and if Yu are adventurous, sliced marinated pig ears.  One little treasure is the Hong Kong style milk tea, served hot or iced.  It is heavenly tasty. This is a restaurant with great prices and wonderful food.

data.title: Stands the test of time!
data.text:
Not a fancy place, but welcoming and always good food and service!   This restaurant
has had the same owners and moved a few times, but it is always consistent.
Food is served hot and you can always upgrade to "spicy" if you ask them.  We have
had many family gatherings around the big round table and have come away satisfied.
The onion pancakes are wonderful, as well as the cashew chicken.  Lunches are affordable
and plentiful.  Parking is easy, but it really fills up during the lunch hour.

data.title: our favorite local chineese place
data.text: toys has been around for decades under the same ownership, very good chineese food for low prices and good service, you can't go wrong if you want chineese.
